ps://roadtostudy.com/#person"},"inLanguage":"en-US"},{"@type":"WebPage","@id":"https://roadtostudy.com/en/health-services-and-pharmaceutical-costs-in-turkey/#webpage","url":"https://roadtostudy.com/en/health-services-and-pharmaceutical-costs-in-turkey/","name":"Health Services and Pharmaceutical Costs in Turkey","datePublished":"2025-10-17T17:45:29+03:00","dateModified":"2026-03-15T21:40:07+03:00","isPartOf":{"@id":"https://roadtostudy.com/#website"},"inLanguage":"en-US"},{"@type":"Person","@id":"https://roadtostudy.com/en/author/murat/","name":"Murat","url":"https://roadtostudy.com/en/author/murat/","image":{"@type":"ImageObject","@id":"https://secure.gravatar.com/avatar/9f5b866231ae7aed7a61015846c1f0ab6c5797b065ec200b93c5e9daa87897af?s=96&amp;d=mm&amp;r=g","url":"https://secure.gravatar.com/avatar/9f5b866231ae7aed7a61015846c1f0ab6c5797b065ec200b93c5e9daa87897af?s=96&amp;d=mm&amp;r=g","caption":"Murat","inLanguage":"en-US"}},{"@type":"BlogPosting","headline":"Health Services and Pharmaceutical Costs in Turkey","keywords":"Pharmaceutical,Health Services","datePublished":"2025-10-17T17:45:29+03:00","dateModified":"2026-03-15T21:40:07+03:00","articleSection":"Cost of Living and Accommodation","author":{"@id":"https://roadtostudy.com/en/author/murat/","name":"Murat"},"publisher":{"@id":"https://roadtostudy.com/#person"},"description":"Learn about healthcare and medicine costs in Turkey. Take the necessary steps to protect your health!","name":"Health Services and Pharmaceutical Costs in Turkey","@id":"https://roadtostudy.com/en/health-services-and-pharmaceutical-costs-in-turkey/#richSnippet","isPartOf":{"@id":"https://roadtostudy.com/en/health-services-and-pharmaceutical-costs-in-turkey/#webpage"},"inLanguage":"en-US","mainEntityOfPage":{"@id":"https://roadtostudy.com/en/health-services-and-pharmaceutical-costs-in-turkey/#webpage"}}]}]}', "content_html" = '<p class="wp-block-paragraph">Turkey is an important destination for both local and international students in terms of healthcare and pharmaceutical costs. In this article, we will conduct a comparative analysis on health services in Turkey, health insurance options for international students, processes of access to health services, per capita health expenditure, and prices of health services and medicines.</p>



<h2 class="wp-block-heading" id="health-services-in-turkey-what-you-need-to-know-for-international-students">Health Services in Turkey: What You Need to Know for International Students</h2>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph">Health services in Turkey are provided by the state and the private sector. Public hospitals provide services for all citizens and foreign residents for a fee. Private hospitals generally offer faster service and comfort. International students need to know some important information in order to benefit from health services in Turkey:</p>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph">&#8211; <strong>State Hospitals</strong>: In Turkey, public hospitals provide the majority of health services. These hospitals, which are affiliated to the Ministry of Health, provide services such as emergencies, examination and treatment.</p>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph">&#8211; <strong>Private Hospitals</strong>: Private hospitals usually offer faster services and provide a comfortable environment. However, the cost of services in these hospitals can be higher.</p>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph">&#8211; <strong>First Aid and Emergency Services</strong>: In Turkey, the 112 emergency service number is used for emergencies. Emergency health services are provided quickly in both public and private hospitals.</p>



<h2 class="wp-block-heading" id="health-insurance-options-for-international-students">Health Insurance Options for International Students</h2>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph">Students coming to Turkey from abroad are required to have health insurance. Health insurance allows students to benefit from necessary health services in case of illness or accident. The health insurance options available in Turkey are:</p>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph">&#8211; <strong>Private Health Insurance</strong>: Private health insurance allows students to receive treatment in private hospitals. This type of insurance usually offers more comprehensive services, but costs more.</p>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph">&#8211; <strong>State Health Insurance</strong>: There are also state health insurance options for foreigners residing in Turkey. This insurance covers services provided at public hospitals and is generally more affordable.</p>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph">&#8211; <strong>International Health Insurance</strong>: Some students may choose to take out international health insurance from insurance companies in their home country. This type of insurance, which usually has broad coverage, is also valid abroad.</p>



<h2 class="wp-block-heading" id="access-to-health-services-in-turkey-visa-process-and-requirements">Access to Health Services in Turkey: Visa Process and Requirements</h2>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph">International students wishing to study in Turkey must first complete the visa process to access healthcare services. The visa process is very important to ensure that students enter Turkey smoothly. Some important points to consider during visa application:</p>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph">&#8211; <strong>Visa Types</strong>: A student visa is usually required to study in Turkey. A student visa allows you to reside in Turkey for the duration of your studies.</p>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph">&#8211; <strong>Required Documents</strong>: Documents required for visa application include an acceptance letter, passport, health insurance and financial qualification documents. Having these documents complete and accurate will help speed up the visa process.</p>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph">&#8211; <strong>Material Qualification</strong>: In order to study in Turkey, you need to have a certain level of financial qualification. The average cost of living in Turkey ranges between 400-800 USD per month. Students are expected to be able to afford the cost of their education.</p>



<h2 class="wp-block-heading" id="how-much-is-the-health-expenditure-per-capita-in-turkey">How Much is the Health Expenditure Per Capita in Turkey?</h2>


<div id="chat-history" class="chat-history-scroll-container">
<div id="1d9d9e838c4c101f" class="conversation-container message-actions-hover-boundary ng-star-inserted">
<div class="response-container ng-tns-c246101515316-23 response-container-with-gpi ng-star-inserted response-container-has-multiple-responses">
<div class="presented-response-container ng-tns-c2461015316-23">
<div class="response-container-content ng-tns-c2461015316-23">
<div class="response-content ng-tns-c246101515316-23">
<div id="model-response-message-contentr_1d9d9e838c4c101f" class="markdown markdown-main-panel stronger enable-updated-hr-color" dir="ltr">According to TurkStat data, per capita health expenditure in Turkey in 2023 was <b>14,582 TL</b>. If we assume that 1 dollar is 42 TL, this expenditure corresponds to approximately <b>347 dollars</b> in dollar terms. <b>Total Health Expenditure:</b> Turkey&#8217;s total health expenditure in 2023 was realized as 1 trillion 244 billion TL. In dollar terms, this corresponds to approximately <b>$29.6 billion</b></div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>


<p class="wp-block-paragraph"></p>



<ul class="wp-block-list">
<li><b>Financing Sources:</b>
<ul class="wp-block-list">
<li>About <b>77.5%</b> of the costs were covered by the state.</li>



<li>The remaining <b>22.5%</b> came from the private sector and households&#8217; own pockets.</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>


</li>
</ul>
<p> These data show that a significant portion of health expenditures in Turkey is covered by the public budget, but households also make a significant contribution to health expenditures. </p></div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>


<h2 class="wp-block-heading" id="health-services-and-drug-prices">Health Services and Drug Prices</h2>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph">Healthcare and medicine prices in Turkey are important issues for both locals and international students. The cost of health services and medicine prices play a critical role in the sustainability of the health system in Turkey.</p>



<h3 class="wp-block-heading" id="medication-prices">Medication Prices</h3>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph">In Turkey, medicine prices are usually regulated by the government. Therefore, medicine prices may be more affordable than in other countries. For example:</p>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph">&#8211; <strong>Prescription Medicines</strong>: The prices of prescription medicines are sold according to the price list set by the government. This reduces the cost of medicines for patients.</p>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph">&#8211; <strong>Over the Counter Medicines</strong>: Over-the-counter medicines are often sold at higher prices, which can be a financial burden for students.</p>



<h3 class="wp-block-heading" id="health-services-prices">Health Services Prices</h3>


<div id="model-response-message-contentr_8fae8c3239e1f148" class="markdown markdown-main-panel stronger enable-updated-hr-color" dir="ltr">


<p class="wp-block-paragraph">Here are the examination fees based on current information for 2025:</p>



<h3 class="wp-block-heading" id="state-hospitals">State Hospitals</h3>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph">Examination fees in public hospitals vary according to the status of the hospital. According to the current Health Implementation Communiqué (SUT) of the Social Security Institution (SSI), the co-payments to be paid for 2025 are as follows:</p>



<ul class="wp-block-list">
<li><b>State Hospitals (Secondary Care):</b> Examination co-payment within the scope of SSI is <b>20 TL</b>.</li>



<li><b>Training and Research Hospitals (Third Level):</b><b>45 TL</b>.</li>
</ul>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph">These fees are well above the range of $0.50 &#8211; $1.25 you mentioned. (Even assuming 1 USD = 42 TL, 20 TL is equivalent to approximately $0.48).</p>



<h3 class="wp-block-heading" id="private-hospitals">Private Hospitals</h3>


<p>The co-payment for examination in private hospitals for SSI patients is <b>50 TL</b>. However, in addition to this fee, there are also difference fees that hospitals can legally charge. These differential fees vary greatly from hospital to hospital and by branch. For example, in some private hospitals, the examination fees alone can vary between <b>1,000 TL and 5,000 TL</b> depending on the branch. This situation arises depending on the quality of service offered by private hospitals and the level of specialization by branch. Therefore, the $5 &#8211; $12.50 you quoted does not reflect current prices. As a result, the information you have shared is out of date and the fees for 2025 are much higher, especially in private hospitals. For the most accurate and precise information, it would be best to contact the hospitals you plan to go directly.</p>
<p>You can also benefit from our article <a title="Discount Shopping Periods for Students in Turkey" href="https://roadtostudy.com/">Discount Shopping Periods for Students in Turkey</a>.</p>


<h2 class="wp-block-heading">Don&#8217;t miss out on affordable treatment and medication options!</h2>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph">Turkey offers many opportunities for international students in terms of healthcare and medicine costs. The services offered by public and private hospitals provide access to quality health services at affordable prices. Health insurance for international students makes it easier for them to benefit from health services. Studying in Turkey offers not only an academic experience but also significant advantages in terms of access to healthcare. Remember, health is paramount; therefore, by carefully evaluating the health care and insurance options in Turkey, you can have a healthy educational life.</p>



<h2 class="wp-block-heading" id="frequently-asked-questions">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>



<h3 class="wp-block-heading" id="how-can-i-benefit-from-health-services-in-turkey">How can I benefit from health services in Turkey?</h3>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph">In order to benefit from health services in Turkey, you must first have health insurance. By choosing between public and private hospitals, you can access health services that meet your needs.</p>



<h3 class="wp-block-heading wp-block-paragraph">Is health insurance compulsory for international students?</h3>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph">Yes, students from abroad are required to have health insurance in order to study in Turkey. This insurance ensures that you receive the necessary health care in the event of illness or accident.</p>



<h3 class="wp-block-heading" id="how-are-medicine-prices-in-turkey">How are medicine prices in Turkey?</h3>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph">In Turkey, medicine prices are regulated by the government. Prescription medicines are usually available at affordable prices, while over-the-counter medicines can be sold at higher prices.</p>



<h3 class="wp-block-heading wp-block-paragraph">How much should I budget for health care?</h3>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph">The budget you need to allocate for healthcare in Turkey can vary depending on the type of hospital you choose and your health insurance coverage. Examination fees vary between 20-50 TL in public hospitals and 200-500 TL in private hospitals.</p>



<h3 class="wp-block-heading" id="what-should-i-do-for-emergencies-in-turkey">What should I do for emergencies in Turkey?</h3>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph">The 112 emergency service number is used in Turkey for emergency situations. Emergency health services are provided quickly in public and private hospitals.</p>', "wp_published_at" = '2025-10-17T14:45:29Z', "wp_modified_at" = '2026-03-15T18:40:07Z' WHERE "deleted_at" IS NULL AND "status" = 'published' AND "locale" = 'en' AND "slug" = 'health-services-and-pharmaceutical-costs-in-turkey';
